{"slideshow_credits": null, "snippet": "Children grow up learning the skills to succeed in their socioeconomic stratum, but not necessarily others, which can deepen class divisions.", "abstract": "The Upshot; Pew Research Center survey finds differences in child rearing in rich and poor American families are growing, symptom of widening inequality with far-reaching consequences; middle-class and higher-income parents view their children as projects that need attentive cultivation, while lower-income parents believe children will naturally prosper and give them more independence.", "section_name": "The Upshot", "print_page": "1", "document_type": "article", "byline": {"person": [{"lastname": "MILLER", "rank": 1, "firstname": "Claire", "role": "reported", "organization": "", "middlename": "Cain"}], "original": "By CLAIRE CAIN MILLER"}, "web_url": "http://www.nytimes.com/2015/12/18/upshot/rich-children-and-poor-ones-are-raised-very-differently.html", "lead_paragraph": "Children grow up learning the skills to succeed in their socioeconomic stratum, but not necessarily others, which can deepen class divisions.", "headline": {"print_headline": "Class Divisions Growing Worse, From Cradle On", "main": "Class Differences in Child-Rearing Are on the Rise", "content_kicker": "Modern Families", "kicker": "The Upshot"}, "_id": "5672ce6938f0d82eed76c683", "word_count": "1235", "multimedia": [{"height": 126, "url": "images/2015/12/15/upshot/00-test-miller/00-test-miller-thumbWide.jpg", "legacy": {"wideheight": "126", "wide": "images/2015/12/15/upshot/00-test-miller/00-test-miller-thumbWide.jpg", "widewidth": "190"}, "subtype": "wide", "width": 190, "type": "image"}, {"height": 896, "url": "images/2015/12/15/upshot/00-test-miller/00-test-miller-articleLarge.jpg", "legacy": {"xlarge": "images/2015/12/15/upshot/00-test-miller/00-test-miller-articleLarge.jpg", "xlargewidth": "600", "xlargeheight": "896"}, "subtype": "xlarge", "width": 600, "type": "image"}, {"height": 75, "url": "imag